WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:01.256
On the evening of July 17,

00:00:01.256 --> 00:00:07.139
1981, about 1,600 people gathered in the atrium

00:00:07.219 --> 00:00:09.990
of the Kansas City Hyatt Regency hotel.

00:00:10.460 --> 00:00:11.421
It was a tea dance.

00:00:12.163 --> 00:00:13.665
The hotel had been open for about a

00:00:13.725 --> 00:00:16.249
year. The atrium was one of the reasons

00:00:16.329 --> 00:00:19.254
people came four stories of open space,

00:00:19.915 --> 00:00:22.539
suspended walkways crossing overhead at the second and

00:00:22.599 --> 00:00:25.203
fourth floors, a room that was designed to

00:00:25.263 --> 00:00:26.284
feel like an occasion.

00:00:27.366 --> 00:00:31.172
At 7:05 PM, the fourth-floor walkway collapsed onto

00:00:31.212 --> 00:00:33.275
the second-floor walkway directly below it.

00:00:33.996 --> 00:00:37.041
Both fell to the atrium floor.

00:00:37.041 --> 00:00:41.387
114 people died. More than 200 were injured.

00:00:42.108 --> 00:00:44.451
It remains one of the deadliest structural failures

00:00:44.531 --> 00:00:47.635
in American history. In the years that followed,

00:00:48.076 --> 00:00:50.459
the investigation focused on a single drawing

00:00:50.539 --> 00:00:53.663
revision. A change to the hanger rod connection

00:00:54.144 --> 00:00:55.967
approved months before the hotel opened,

00:00:56.547 --> 00:00:58.190
flagged by no one as significant,

00:00:58.890 --> 00:01:01.494
categorized internally as a fabrication convenience.

00:01:02.435 --> 00:01:04.598
That revision doubled the load on a connection

00:01:04.638 --> 00:01:06.741
that was already insufficient.

00:01:06.856 --> 00:01:09.178
This episode is not about a reckless decision

00:01:09.218 --> 00:01:10.720
or a corrupt company.

00:01:11.581 --> 00:01:14.384
It is about something quieter and more dangerous:

00:01:15.265 --> 00:01:17.787
how a structural redesign moved through a system

00:01:17.827 --> 00:01:19.809
that had lost the ability to recognize it

00:01:19.909 --> 00:01:23.993
as one. The Hyatt Regency Kansas City opened

00:01:24.053 --> 00:01:27.457
in July 1980. The atrium was the architectural

00:01:27.517 --> 00:01:30.860
centerpiece roughly 145 feet long,

00:01:30.880 --> 00:01:35.445
117 feet wide, and 50 feet high.

00:01:36.269 --> 00:01:38.513
The suspended walkways were a deliberate visual

00:01:38.594 --> 00:01:40.778
feature. They were meant to be seen.

00:01:40.798 --> 00:01:43.684
They crossed the atrium at the second and

00:01:43.744 --> 00:01:47.191
fourth floors, attached to the ceiling structure above

00:01:47.271 --> 00:01:49.936
by vertical hanger rods, and they gave the

00:01:49.996 --> 00:01:53.503
space the feeling of movement and scale that

00:01:53.543 --> 00:01:57.090
the design intended. The structural system for those

00:01:57.130 --> 00:01:58.893
walkways was not unusual.

00:01:59.935 --> 00:02:03.081
Suspended walkways carried by hanger rods were a

00:02:03.161 --> 00:02:06.868
known engineering solution. The design called for a

00:02:06.949 --> 00:02:09.433
series of rods running vertically from the ceiling

00:02:09.513 --> 00:02:12.519
framing, passing through the box beams of the

00:02:12.579 --> 00:02:15.865
fourth-floor walkway, and continuing down to the box

00:02:15.945 --> 00:02:17.869
beams of the second-floor walkway.

00:02:18.625 --> 00:02:21.308
In the original design, each rod was a

00:02:21.408 --> 00:02:25.133
single continuous element. It ran from the ceiling

00:02:25.173 --> 00:02:28.376
connection, through both levels, with a nut and

00:02:28.436 --> 00:02:30.879
washer bearing against the underside of each box

00:02:30.939 --> 00:02:33.683
beam. The logic of that system is worth

00:02:33.763 --> 00:02:36.846
pausing on. In the original configuration,

00:02:37.567 --> 00:02:39.589
the fourth-floor box beam carried only the

00:02:39.649 --> 00:02:43.053
fourth-floor walkway. The nut at the fourth floor

00:02:43.053 --> 00:02:45.176
bore only against the dead load and live

00:02:45.216 --> 00:02:46.978
load of that structure.

00:02:47.212 --> 00:02:49.438
The weight of the second-floor walkway was carried

00:02:49.538 --> 00:02:52.205
separately further down the same rod,

00:02:52.245 --> 00:02:53.789
at a different bearing point,

00:02:54.431 --> 00:02:55.815
closer to the load itself.

00:02:56.777 --> 00:02:59.224
This matters. Keep it in mind.

00:03:00.828 --> 00:03:03.439
During the shop drawing phase the period when

00:03:03.479 --> 00:03:06.302
a fabricator translates a structural engineer's design

00:03:06.362 --> 00:03:09.466
into construction-ready drawings Havens Steel,

00:03:09.926 --> 00:03:13.230
the steel contractor, raised a practical concern.

00:03:14.011 --> 00:03:17.295
The original hanger rod design required threading a

00:03:17.375 --> 00:03:19.898
single rod for nearly its full length so

00:03:19.938 --> 00:03:21.440
that a nut could be seated at both

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:24.964
the fourth-floor and second-floor connections.

00:03:24.964 --> 00:03:26.729
Threading a long rod is difficult.

00:03:27.331 --> 00:03:29.376
The threads are vulnerable to damage during

00:03:29.437 --> 00:03:32.846
installation. The fabrication was inconvenient.

00:03:33.688 --> 00:03:37.038
Havens proposed a revision: instead of one long

00:03:37.118 --> 00:03:39.645
rod, use two shorter ones.

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:41.823
The upper rod would run from the ceiling

00:03:41.883 --> 00:03:43.325
to the fourth-floor box beam.

00:03:44.186 --> 00:03:46.129
A second rod would run from the fourth-floor

00:03:46.209 --> 00:03:49.514
box beam down to the second floor.

00:03:49.514 --> 00:03:52.038
On paper, this looked like a minor adjustment.

00:03:52.839 --> 00:03:54.582
The geometry was nearly identical.

00:03:55.363 --> 00:03:57.406
The walkways would hang in the same positions.

00:03:58.147 --> 00:03:59.829
The visual result was unchanged.

00:04:00.571 --> 00:04:02.954
A shop drawing reflecting the revision was submitted

00:04:02.994 --> 00:04:04.577
to the engineering firm for review.

00:04:04.637 --> 00:04:08.282
It was approved with no load recalculation.

00:04:08.414 --> 00:04:10.156
Here is what the revision actually did.

00:04:11.719 --> 00:04:14.803
In the original design, the fourth-floor box beam

00:04:14.843 --> 00:04:16.385
connection carried one walkway.

00:04:17.346 --> 00:04:20.290
In the revised design, the upper rod terminated

00:04:20.330 --> 00:04:21.752
at the fourth-floor box beam,

00:04:22.533 --> 00:04:24.636
which meant the fourth-floor connection now had to

00:04:24.676 --> 00:04:27.961
carry both walkways. The second-floor walkway no

00:04:28.021 --> 00:04:30.104
longer hung from the same rod below the

00:04:30.104 --> 00:04:33.328
fourth floor. It hung from the fourth-floor structure

00:04:33.408 --> 00:04:37.027
itself. The load at the fourth-floor connection did

00:04:37.087 --> 00:04:39.592
not increase marginally. It doubled.

00:04:40.353 --> 00:04:43.339
The connection a nut and washer bearing against

00:04:43.359 --> 00:04:45.824
the bottom flange of a box beam fabricated

00:04:45.884 --> 00:04:49.531
from two channel sections was not redesigned to

00:04:49.591 --> 00:04:53.017
accommodate this. No one performed an independent

00:04:53.057 --> 00:04:55.502
calculation of what the revised detail was now

00:04:55.582 --> 00:04:56.764
being asked to hold.

00:04:57.740 --> 00:04:59.262
To understand how this happened,

00:04:59.683 --> 00:05:01.606
you have to look past the revision itself.

00:05:02.607 --> 00:05:04.570
The revision was the mechanism of failure.

00:05:05.471 --> 00:05:07.835
But five separate conditions had to be true

00:05:07.935 --> 00:05:09.958
for it to pass through the system unchecked.

00:05:10.899 --> 00:05:14.905
The first: ownership of the revision was ambiguous.

00:05:15.273 --> 00:05:17.055
On a large construction project,

00:05:17.736 --> 00:05:20.780
shop drawings pass between the fabricator and the

00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:24.085
engineer of record. The engineer's review stamp is

00:05:24.165 --> 00:05:26.788
typically understood as confirmation that the drawing

00:05:26.868 --> 00:05:30.012
conforms to the design intent not a full

00:05:30.092 --> 00:05:31.855
independent check of every detail.

00:05:32.916 --> 00:05:35.399
The fabricator's role is to propose practical

00:05:35.479 --> 00:05:38.845
solutions; the engineer's role is to catch problems.

00:05:39.726 --> 00:05:42.570
In practice, this split creates a gap.

00:05:43.511 --> 00:05:46.015
When Havens submitted the revised rod detail,

00:05:46.736 --> 00:05:49.239
the question of who was responsible for verifying

00:05:49.279 --> 00:05:51.642
the load path had no clear answer.

00:05:52.584 --> 00:05:55.067
The fabricator had proposed a convenience change.

00:05:55.768 --> 00:05:57.551
The engineer had stamped the drawing.

00:05:58.512 --> 00:06:00.755
Neither party had performed the calculation that would

00:06:00.775 --> 00:06:02.998
have immediately revealed the problem.

00:06:03.350 --> 00:06:05.653
Ownership of the revision was distributed in a

00:06:05.713 --> 00:06:08.757
way that, in effect, meant no one owned

00:06:08.817 --> 00:06:13.242
it completely. The second: the change was framed

00:06:13.322 --> 00:06:16.446
as fabrication convenience, not redesign.

00:06:17.467 --> 00:06:19.390
Language matters in engineering review.

00:06:19.410 --> 00:06:22.734
A fabrication accommodation moves through a system

00:06:22.814 --> 00:06:25.257
differently than a structural revision.

00:06:25.523 --> 00:06:27.746
The first category implies that the intent is

00:06:27.846 --> 00:06:30.250
preserved and only the method is adjusted.

00:06:31.111 --> 00:06:32.933
The second implies that the behavior of the

00:06:32.993 --> 00:06:35.237
system may have changed and needs to be

00:06:35.277 --> 00:06:38.962
verified. The revised rod detail was categorized,

00:06:39.322 --> 00:06:42.166
implicitly, as the first kind of change.

00:06:43.208 --> 00:06:44.950
It looked like a threading convenience.

00:06:45.671 --> 00:06:48.135
It was presented as a threading convenience.

00:06:48.996 --> 00:06:50.939
The framing suppressed the question that should have

00:06:50.959 --> 00:06:53.962
been asked: does this change the load path?

00:06:54.944 --> 00:06:58.308
It did. Substantially. The third:

00:06:58.328 --> 00:07:02.253
no independent load calculation was performed on the

00:07:02.293 --> 00:07:05.557
revised connection. This is the clearest failure in

00:07:05.597 --> 00:07:08.340
the chain, and it is also the most

00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:12.085
structurally important. The Kansas City building code

00:07:12.145 --> 00:07:14.748
at the time required walkway connections to support

00:07:14.828 --> 00:07:16.911
twice the expected live load.

00:07:17.549 --> 00:07:20.274
The original design, even before the revision,

00:07:20.334 --> 00:07:23.681
only met roughly 60 percent of that requirement.

00:07:24.402 --> 00:07:25.685
It was already undersized.

00:07:26.366 --> 00:07:29.192
The revised connection, which doubled the load on

00:07:29.212 --> 00:07:32.238
the fourth-floor bearing point, dropped that margin to

00:07:32.298 --> 00:07:34.883
roughly 30 percent of the required capacity.

00:07:35.639 --> 00:07:37.481
Had anyone run the numbers on the revised

00:07:37.541 --> 00:07:41.486
detail a straightforward calculation, not an advanced

00:07:41.646 --> 00:07:44.189
one the deficiency would have been apparent.

00:07:45.150 --> 00:07:46.451
The check was never performed.

00:07:47.172 --> 00:07:49.394
The revision moved through approval as a drawing,

00:07:50.035 --> 00:07:52.818
not as a structural change that required structural

00:07:52.878 --> 00:07:57.463
verification. The fourth: earlier warning signs during

00:07:57.504 --> 00:08:01.528
construction did not trigger deeper scrutiny.

00:08:01.528 --> 00:08:04.712
In October 1979, during construction,

00:08:05.433 --> 00:08:07.956
a section of the atrium roof collapsed.

00:08:08.677 --> 00:08:11.140
The failure was attributed to a connection problem

00:08:11.601 --> 00:08:14.264
and addressed. Construction continued.

00:08:14.985 --> 00:08:17.108
This is not an uncommon pattern in large

00:08:17.168 --> 00:08:20.432
projects. Partial failures during construction are

00:08:20.472 --> 00:08:24.577
investigated, corrected, and treated as isolated

00:08:24.637 --> 00:08:28.162
events rather than signals about system-level

00:08:28.202 --> 00:08:31.414
weakness. The roof collapse did not prompt a

00:08:31.474 --> 00:08:32.796
review of the walkway design.

00:08:33.638 --> 00:08:35.762
The two events were categorized separately.

00:08:36.824 --> 00:08:39.168
When warning signs are absorbed as individual

00:08:39.248 --> 00:08:42.474
incidents rather than read as evidence about the

00:08:42.594 --> 00:08:44.056
overall margin of the system,

00:08:44.658 --> 00:08:47.302
the system loses its best opportunity to find

00:08:47.382 --> 00:08:51.630
problems before they become failures.

00:08:51.630 --> 00:08:53.774
The fifth: the original design had insufficient

00:08:53.814 --> 00:08:56.918
margin, so the revision made a vulnerable system

00:08:57.018 --> 00:08:59.942
lethal. Every failure has a threshold.

00:09:00.783 --> 00:09:03.266
The Hyatt walkways were not hovering at adequate

00:09:03.326 --> 00:09:04.888
margin when the revision arrived.

00:09:05.588 --> 00:09:06.970
They were already below code.

00:09:07.731 --> 00:09:09.914
The revised connection did not push a safe

00:09:09.974 --> 00:09:13.338
system into danger. It pushed an already-deficient

00:09:13.438 --> 00:09:16.862
system into certainty. This is a recurring pattern

00:09:16.922 --> 00:09:19.986
in structural failures. The final cause is often

00:09:20.086 --> 00:09:20.967
not the only cause.

00:09:21.728 --> 00:09:23.910
The thing that triggers the collapse is frequently

00:09:24.090 --> 00:09:26.213
acting on a structure that has been accumulating

00:09:26.293 --> 00:09:27.715
vulnerability from the beginning.

00:09:28.536 --> 00:09:29.998
The redesign doubled the load.

00:09:30.758 --> 00:09:32.681
The original load was already too much.

00:09:33.462 --> 00:09:35.544
The Kansas City Hyatt walkway collapse was

00:09:35.624 --> 00:09:38.928
investigated thoroughly. The engineering firm lost its

00:09:39.028 --> 00:09:42.913
licenses. Lawsuits proceeded for years.

00:09:42.913 --> 00:09:45.536
The revision was identified quickly as the proximate

00:09:45.596 --> 00:09:48.960
cause. But the investigation also surfaced something

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:52.143
harder to resolve: no single person had made

00:09:52.183 --> 00:09:54.686
a decision to approve an obviously dangerous

00:09:54.706 --> 00:09:57.910
structure. The revision had moved through a system.

00:09:58.811 --> 00:10:01.053
Each handoff had occurred within its expected

00:10:01.113 --> 00:10:04.898
category. No one had acted with obvious negligence

00:10:04.978 --> 00:10:07.100
in their own framing of what they were

00:10:07.140 --> 00:10:11.365
reviewing. The structural failure was not hidden.

00:10:11.986 --> 00:10:14.029
Any engineer who ran a load calculation on

00:10:14.049 --> 00:10:16.692
the revised detail would have found it immediately.

00:10:16.712 --> 00:10:20.757
The failure was hidden from the process absorbed

00:10:20.797 --> 00:10:23.521
into a category labeled routine before it could

00:10:23.541 --> 00:10:25.383
be evaluated as structural.

00:10:26.284 --> 00:10:28.206
This is what the shop drawing process was

00:10:28.287 --> 00:10:31.270
designed to catch. This is exactly what it

00:10:31.350 --> 00:10:34.254
failed to catch. When we tell this story

00:10:34.334 --> 00:10:37.198
as a single-cause failure, we miss what it

00:10:37.298 --> 00:10:40.414
actually demonstrates. It is tempting to say:

00:10:40.454 --> 00:10:42.718
someone should have checked the math.

00:10:43.540 --> 00:10:46.465
That is true. But it is not sufficient.

00:10:47.387 --> 00:10:49.551
Because the math was checkable at every stage,

00:10:50.051 --> 00:10:52.676
by multiple parties, and was not checked by

00:10:52.816 --> 00:10:55.992
any of them. The question that explains the

00:10:56.072 --> 00:10:59.516
failure is not who forgot the calculation.

00:10:59.556 --> 00:11:02.640
It is why the system did not require

00:11:02.801 --> 00:11:05.824
one. A revision that changes the load path

00:11:05.904 --> 00:11:09.028
of a life-safety connection is a structural redesign.

00:11:09.869 --> 00:11:11.632
It does not matter that it was proposed

00:11:11.712 --> 00:11:13.975
as a fabrication convenience.

00:11:13.995 --> 00:11:16.338
It does not matter that it looked geometrically

00:11:16.438 --> 00:11:18.240
similar to the original.

00:11:18.240 --> 00:11:20.523
The moment the load at the fourth-floor connection

00:11:20.583 --> 00:11:23.786
doubled, the detail had to be evaluated as

00:11:23.887 --> 00:11:24.487
if it were new.

00:11:25.508 --> 00:11:28.171
The system had no reliable mechanism for recognizing

00:11:28.212 --> 00:11:31.956
that moment. In software, this is a known

00:11:32.096 --> 00:11:35.860
failure mode: a patch that seems local turns

00:11:35.961 --> 00:11:37.522
out to have non-local effects.

00:11:38.604 --> 00:11:41.146
In medicine, it appears when a drug interaction

00:11:41.227 --> 00:11:44.130
is missed because two prescribers are reviewing the

00:11:44.170 --> 00:11:47.629
same patient separately. In regulatory systems,

00:11:48.410 --> 00:11:50.192
it appears when a rule written for one

00:11:50.372 --> 00:11:52.494
era of scale gets applied to a structure

00:11:53.095 --> 00:11:54.817
the rule was never designed to cover.

00:11:55.637 --> 00:11:57.699
The form is always the same.

00:11:58.901 --> 00:12:00.803
A change is framed in a category that

00:12:00.863 --> 00:12:02.644
does not require deep review.

00:12:03.605 --> 00:12:04.787
The category is wrong.

00:12:05.587 --> 00:12:06.969
The system has no way to know it

00:12:07.049 --> 00:12:10.332
is wrong, because the category itself is the

00:12:10.372 --> 00:12:13.135
gate through which the change passes.

00:12:13.925 --> 00:12:17.150
The Hyatt Regency walkways did not fail because

00:12:17.190 --> 00:12:19.653
someone chose to cut corners on a calculation

00:12:19.713 --> 00:12:20.915
they knew was necessary.

00:12:21.937 --> 00:12:24.320
They failed because the process had been organized

00:12:24.420 --> 00:12:26.083
in a way that made the calculation feel

00:12:26.203 --> 00:12:28.847
unnecessary and no one in the chain was

00:12:28.927 --> 00:12:31.210
positioned to see the whole picture clearly enough

00:12:31.290 --> 00:12:35.386
to know otherwise. Fourteen months after the hotel

00:12:35.546 --> 00:12:38.051
opened, the atrium was full of people on

00:12:38.091 --> 00:12:41.197
a summer evening, standing on and below structures

00:12:41.257 --> 00:12:42.179
that could not hold them.

00:12:43.021 --> 00:12:45.446
The shop drawing that approved the revised connection

00:12:45.987 --> 00:12:48.011
had been stamped and filed.

00:12:48.752 --> 00:12:50.075
The construction was complete.

00:12:50.736 --> 00:12:52.740
Inspections had been passed.

00:12:52.740 --> 00:12:53.882
Everything was in order.

00:12:54.564 --> 00:12:55.806
That is not a reassurance.

00:12:56.467 --> 00:12:57.329
That is the problem.

00:12:58.091 --> 00:13:00.034
What failed in Kansas City was not the

00:13:00.074 --> 00:13:03.281
calculation. Calculations were never the bottleneck.

00:13:04.002 --> 00:13:07.128
What failed was the system's ability to recognize

00:13:07.188 --> 00:13:10.054
when a change had crossed a category boundary

00:13:10.523 --> 00:13:13.248
when something labeled routine had become structural,

00:13:13.909 --> 00:13:15.693
and when the margin that should have absorbed

00:13:15.713 --> 00:13:17.556
the error had already been spent.

00:13:18.598 --> 00:13:21.163
The walkways were compliant in the sense that

00:13:21.203 --> 00:13:23.547
they had passed through every required gate.

00:13:24.229 --> 00:13:26.453
They were lethal in the sense that no

00:13:26.533 --> 00:13:28.597
required gate had been designed to catch this

00:13:28.697 --> 00:13:30.220
particular kind of failure.

00:13:31.043 --> 00:13:34.454
The revision that killed 114 people was a

00:13:34.574 --> 00:13:36.721
drawing change that went through normal channels,

00:13:37.202 --> 00:13:39.790
in normal time, and was approved by people

00:13:39.850 --> 00:13:41.154
doing what their role required.

00:13:41.917 --> 00:13:44.585
The system worked exactly as designed.

00:13:45.367 --> 00:13:46.110
That was the problem.

00:13:47.253 --> 00:13:49.580
Next time: another design failure.

00:13:50.262 --> 00:13:52.590
Another system that taught itself to ignore what

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:53.693
it already knew.
